  <h1>Common Property Damage Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;My insurance will pay full replacement cost.&rdquo;</h2><p>Only if you have an RCV endorsement. Standard policies pay ACV — replacement cost minus depreciation. For older property, this can be a fraction of the replacement cost. Check your declarations page and upgrade to RCV coverage if you don&rsquo;t have it.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Flood damage is covered by homeowners insurance.&rdquo;</h2><p>Standard homeowners insurance does not cover flood damage. Flood insurance must be purchased separately through the National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP) or private insurers. Water damage from a burst pipe (internal cause) is typically covered; water damage from rising floodwaters is not.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;The insurer&rsquo;s total loss determination is final.&rdquo;</h2><p>You can dispute a total loss determination. Get independent repair estimates from certified mechanics. Research comparable vehicles to challenge the insurer&rsquo;s ACV calculation. Use the appraisal clause in your policy to invoke a neutral appraiser process.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t claim diminished value.&rdquo;</h2><p>You can claim DV from the at-fault driver&rsquo;s insurer in most states. Insurers often deny or lowball DV claims initially — persistence and an independent appraisal usually produce better results.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-property-damage-claims-work">how claims work</a> and <a href="/guides/rcv-vs-acv">RCV vs. ACV</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
